revision.text:
The '''1465 Moroccan revolt''' refers to a popular revolt by local Sharifs in [[Fes]] who overthrew the last [[Marinid]] sultan.<ref name="Isichei1997">{{cite book|last=Isichei|first=Elizabeth Allo|title=A History of African Societies to 1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3C2tzBSAp3MC&pg=PA190|accessdate=23 April 2012|date=13 April 1997|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-45599-2|page=190}}</ref> The revolt marked the end of a 215-year reign (1244–1465). The sharifs formed a ''[[jihad]]'', against the last Marinid leader, a [[Jewish]] vizir, [[Aaron ben Batash]], appointed by [[Abd al-Haqq II|Abu Muhammad Abd Al-Haqq]]. They subsequently put him to death, cutting his throat. Almost all the Jewish community of [[Fes]] were also slaughtered in the revolt.<ref name="Haddad1984">{{cite book|last=Haddad|first=Heskel M.|title=Jews of Arab and Islamic countries: history, problems, solutions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N5dtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=23 April 2012|year=1984|publisher=Shengold Publishers|isbn=978-0-88400-100-3|page=75}}</ref> As a result of the troubles in Fes, the Portuguese king [[Afonso V of Portugal|Afonso V]] finally managed to take [[Tangier]].
After the execution of Abd al-Haqq, Muhammad b. Imran, head of the [[Idrissid]] ''shurafas'' of Fes, was proclaimed Sultan.<ref name="Bennison2002">{{cite book|last=Bennison|first=Amira K.|title=Jihad and Its Interpretations in Pre-Colonial Morocco: State-Society Relations During the French Conquest of Algeria|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2rwZEbR0_w0C&pg=PA19|accessdate=23 April 2012|date=28 October 2002|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-7007-1693-7|page=19}}</ref><ref name="Image">Herman L. Beck, L'image d'Idrīs II, ses descendants de Fās et la politique sharīfienne des sultans marīnides, 656-869/1258-1465, BRILL 1989, pp.250-255 [https://books.google.com/books?hl=fr&lr=&id=1eW1fjoCbDwC&oi=fnd&pg=PR198#v=onepage&q&f=false]</ref> However a "struggle for power ensued between the Idrisi ''shurafa'' and the [[Wattasid]] ''mujahids'' ".<ref name="Bennison2002"/> He was in turn overthrown in 1472 by the [[Wattasid dynasty|Wattasid]] [[Abu Abd Allah al-Sheikh Muhammad ibn Yahya]], one of the two Wattasid vizirs surviving the [[1459 massacre]].
Abu Abd Allah continued somewhat unsuccessfully to advocate Marinid policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://etheses.whiterose.ac.uk/348/1/uk_bl_ethos_426809.pdf |title=An architectural Investigation of Marinid and Watasid Fes |page=5|publisher=Etheses.whiterose.ac.uk|accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref> The Wattasids were eventually expelled from Morocco by the Saadi sharifs in 1554.<ref name="Overy2007">{{cite book|last=Overy|first=R. J.|title=Complete History of the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cbc87C11DMgC&pg=PA373|accessdate=23 April 2012|year=2007|publisher=Times Books|isbn=978-0-00-725927-4|page=373}}</ref>
