{{infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = Chaka | title_orig = | translator = F. H. Dutton | image = Thomas Mofolo Chaka.jpg | caption = | author = [[Thomas Mofolo]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[Lesotho]] | language = [[Sotho language|Sotho]] | series = | genre = | publisher = | release_date = 1925 | english_release_date = 1931 | media_type = | pages = 168 | isbn = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Chaka''''' is the most famous novel by the writer [[Thomas Mofolo]] of [[Lesotho]]. Written in [[Sotho language|Sotho]], it is a mythic retelling of the story of the rise and fall of the [[Zulu Kingdom|Zulu]] emperor-king [[Shaka]]. It was named one of the twelve best works of [[African literature]] of the 20th century by a panel organized by [[Ali Mazrui]].<ref>List available at [http://library.columbia.edu/content/libraryweb/indiv/global/cuvl/african_studies/books.html Columbia University Library website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302125917/http://library.columbia.edu/content/libraryweb/indiv/global/cuvl/african_studies/books.html |date=March 2, 2013 }}.</ref> The book has been translated into English on two separate occasions. Originally translated by F. H. Dutton, it was first published in 1931 by [[Oxford University Press]]. In 1981 it was published in [[Heinemann (publisher)|Heinemann]]'s [[African Writers Series]].
