{{Infobox motorsport championship | logo = Superstars World logo.jpeg | category = [[Touring car racing|Touring cars]] | country/region = International | inaugural = 2004 | folded = 2013 | drivers = 28 (2014) | teams = 10 (2013) | manufactures = 6 (2013): Audi, BMW, Chevrolet, Chrysler, Lexus, Mercedes | engines = | tyres = [[Hankook]] | champion driver = {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Francesco Sini]] | champion team = {{flagicon|ITA}} Audi Sport Italia | current_season = | website = [http://www.superstarsworld.com www.superstarsworld.com] }}
The '''Superstars International Series''' was a production-based [[touring car racing]] championship held between 2004 and 2013. It was managed by the "Superstars World of Racing SpA", SWR, a company of FG GROUP with headquarters in Rome<ref>{{cite web|title=FG Group|url=http://www.gruppofg.com|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315170206/http://www.gruppofg.com/|archivedate=2013-03-15|df=}}</ref> and sanctioned by the [[Automobile Club d'Italia]] (ACI) and the [[Commissione Sportiva Automobilistica Italiana]] (CSAI).<ref>[http://www.eurosuperstars.com/eng/db.pdf 2009 Superstars Marketing Presentation] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419062601/http://www.eurosuperstars.com/eng/db.pdf |date=April 19, 2009 }}</ref> FG GROUP, led by [[Maurizio Flammini]], is famous for having promoted the FIM [[World Superbike Championship]] from its beginnings in 1988 until its sale to [[Infront Sports & Media]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Motors TV|url=http://www.motorstv.com/bike/road-racing/wsbk-ssp/01112008/fg-sport-become-infront-motor-sports|title=FG Sport become Infront Motor Sports}}</ref>
[[File:Superstars Series logo.jpg|thumb|Superstars Series logo used from 2010 to 2011]]
After the shutdown of the promoter SWR in late 2013, the competition has been re-branded as '''[[2014 EuroV8 Series|EuroV8 Series]]''' and organized by FG Group and ATT (Associazione Team Top cars). '''SuperTouringSeries''' is going to be performed by ''Pan Asia Racing Enterprise Ltd. (PARE Ltd)'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/2014/01/25/new-eurov8-series-to-fill-in-for-superstars-in-2014/|title=New EUROV8 SERIES to fill-in for Superstars in 2014|last=Hudson|first=Neil|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|date=25 January 2014|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> However, it has been cancelled.
The new championship’s identity, partners, teams, sporting regulations and calendar will be unveiled at the Autosport International show in January.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/2013/12/04/supertouringseries-to-take-over-from-superstars/|title=SuperTouringSeries to take over from Superstars|last=Hudson|first=Neil|date=4 December 2013|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB}}</ref>
==History== The series began in 2004 as '''Trofeo Nazionale Superstars''' (Superstars National Trophy) with a six race schedule, all the events held in Italian tracks. The initial field was made of BMW M5 and Jaguar S-Type models, entered by five teams.
Since 2005 the series earned the '''Campionato Italiano Superstars''' (Italian Superstars Championship) title, and soon became the main tin-top auto racing series of the country, replacing the [[Italian Superturismo Championship]] (folded in 2007).
[[File:Thomas-biagi.JPG|thumb|[[BMW]] racing in the Superstars Series]] In 2007 the series started to visit circuits in other European countries with the [[FIA]] approved '''International Superstars Series'''. Since then every season awards two different drivers' titles, one for the International Series and one for the Italian Championship. Points are gained for the Italian Championship at each Italian and one European race meeting.
With the 2010 season a new series was added, the '''[[International GTSprint Series]]''' allowing [[Group GT2|GT2]], [[Group GT3|GT3]] and nationally-homologated GTs. Uniquely, however, it has two 25 minute sprint events per weekend rather than the usual two-driver, long-distance runs that are the norm in GT competition.
The 2012 season saw the growth of the series in terms of media and spectators - attracting 33,000 fans to its race at Vallelunga in Rome on October 7, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Omni Corse|title=33,000 a Vallelunga|url=http://www.omnicorse.it/magazine/22193/superstars-ben-33000-spettatori-per-la-tappa-di-vallelunga|publisher=Omni Corse|accessdate=2013-02-25}}</ref> Johan Kristoffersson won the championship in his KMS Audi RS5 after a season long battle with Vitantonio Liuzzi and his CAAL Racing Mercedes AMG C63. Kristoffersson's success in Superstars proved a strong element in advancing his career.<ref>{{cite web|last=SUPERSTARS|title=SUPERSTARSWORLD a perfect fit for young racers|url=http://www.superstarsworld.com/Superstars-Series/News/SUPERSTARSWORLD-a-perfect-fit-for-young-racers.aspx|accessdate=2013-02-25}}</ref>
The 2013 calendar contains eight races in 6 countries. The series promoters have given the series an umbrella name "The Superstars World of Racing" that reflects its international growth and refers to the entire weekend of events which includes The Superstars International Series, the GT Sprint International Series, local support races and entertainment events.<ref>{{cite web|last=SUPERSTARS PRESS OFFICE|url=http://www.superstarsworld.com/Superstars-Series/News/SUPERSTARSWORLD-reveals-combined-schedule-for-2013.aspx|title={{-"}}SUPERSTARSWORLD" reveals combined schedule for 2013 SUPERSTARS, GTSPRINT INTERNATIONAL SERIES}}</ref>
==Format and Philosophy== [[File:Steven goldstein audi rs4 pilot colombia.jpg|thumb|Audi RS4 of the Superstars Series]] Since 2009 the Series has run a two sprint race format. Race 1 to take place Sunday morning and Race 2 to take place Sunday afternoon.
The technical regulations are designed to bring the largest touring cars together in a balanced competition that limits costs, maximizes spectacle and limits driver assistance. A total of 10 brands will be represented in the 2013 edition: Audi RS5, BMW M3, Cadillac CTS-V, Chevrolet Lumina and Camaro, Chrysler 300C SRT8, Jaguar XF, Lexus ISF, Maserati Quattroporte, Mercedes C63AMG, Porsche Panamera.<ref>{{cite web|last=SUPERSTARS|first=MARKETING OFFICE|title=2013 Brochure|url=http://www.superstarsworld.com/Resources/2013-SUPERSTARSWORLD-PRESENTATION.aspx|publisher=SWR SpA|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>{{update inline|date=October 2016}}
==Technical regulations==
===Current season=== The 2013 Superstars championships are reserved for production-based saloon cars with the following basic characteristics: *Otto cycle engines with 6 to 12 cylinders (Wankel engines not allowed) *forced induction (turbochargers or superchargers) allowed if used in the production car *minimum displacement of 3800 cc *production H-pattern gearbox or approved mechanical sequential gearbox (automatic and semiautomatic transmission are forbidden) *four or two doors body style *homologated for at least 4 passengers Each homologated car must comply with a ''technical sheet'' issued by the Permanent Bureau, which contains the technical description of all the car's components, both originals and belonging to technical kits.
